### Part X — Loom Website

The website is the woven book, running — the pages you are reading now. `loom weave` projects the corpus into a `WovenCorpus`; a small Effect backend serves it, and a Foldkit application renders it: a landing that fronts the site, a top bar with a theme switch, a sidebar of parts and chapters, the reading column, and an outline of the current page. The client ships without the book — each page's data arrives from the backend and the corpus is read a page at a time, so the bundle stays small. One design system dresses every surface, a warm-paper light theme and a deep editor-slate dark, both drawn from a single vocabulary of tokens. This part builds it up — the tokens and their two themes, the shared model, the reading application, the landing, the page it mounts into, the backend that serves it, and the package that ships them together.

1. The theme system
2. The model
3. The reading app
4. The landing
5. The page
6. The backend
7. Packaging the website
8. The pre-render
9. The image

### Part XI — Loom Devtools

Loom Devtools rides along a running app: a bar you summon over the page to work on the app while you use it. It works against any app — woven from Loom or not — and writes nothing into the code you review. The bar gathers a few tools and is built to hold more. Today it carries Notes: you review by pointing, leaving a note on an element you click or a message you type, and a coding agent reads them over the Model Context Protocol and works through them. There are two ways to run it. The stack-agnostic one is a standalone service — a Bun server backed by Postgres, shipped as a Docker image and run with `docker compose` — that any app talks to. The other is a Vite plugin that runs the same server inside a Vite project's own dev server, over a SQLite file, so a TypeScript app carries the Devtools with nothing else to start. This part builds it up: the note the tools pass around, the store that keeps the notes — in Postgres for the service, a SQLite file for the plugin — the server that answers the overlay and the agent, the overlay you point with, the agent's tools, and the Vite plugin that runs it. It then ships the service — the package, the local Postgres stack, the entry that launches it, the Docker image, and the setup page that hands you the overlay's script — all as `@athrio/loom-devtools`.

1. The note
2. The store
3. The server
4. The overlay
5. The agent's tools
6. The Vite plugin
7. Packaging
8. The local stack
9. The service entry
10. The image
11. The setup UI

### Part XII — Releasing Loom

Loom releases itself on every push. A gate runs first — the tests, and a check that the committed source still matches the corpus it tangles from — and a green push to the default branch releases. It publishes the npm packages through Trusted Publishing, so no token lives in the repository, and pushes the Docker images for the Devtools service and the website. This part is that pipeline: the gate that guards every change, the tool that publishes each package npm is missing, and the workflow that runs it and pushes the images on a push.

1. Continuous integration
2. The release tool
3. Releasing on a push

### Part XIII — Loom UI

The design catalog, the reading website, and the demos beside them are all Foldkit applications, and they dress in the same components. This part is that shared wardrobe, `@athrio/loom-ui`: a theme system, a set of components, and the submodels among them. A component reads the theme's tokens for its look and takes the rest as properties, so the same button belongs on a warm-paper page and a deep-slate one, in any application. The library is the source; an application only consumes it. This part builds it up — the theme system and its light and dark modes, the presentational components that hold no state, the interactive ones that report a message but keep none, the window chrome that frames every surface, the code surface that paints highlighted source, the copy button and the command palette that own their own state as submodels, and the package that ships them together.

1. The theme system
2. Presentational components
3. Interactive components
4. The copy button
5. The command palette
6. Window chrome
7. The code surface
8. Packaging Loom UI

### Part XIV — The landing

The landing is the front page of the site, rebuilt as a Foldkit application: the window chrome, a hero whose headline rotates a word beside a live editor panel, a manifesto after Knuth, a walk through the pipeline with a searchable command palette, a get-started with a config and a quick start, and a footer. It renders on the server first, for a reader and a crawler, then hydrates and takes over — the tabs, the file tree, the palette, and the copy buttons come alive, while the rotating word and the typing line run on their own. It holds its own components for now, local to the landing, to be lifted into the shared library once the rest of the site joins them. This part builds it up — the stylesheet, the model, the local components, the hero, the manifesto and how-it-works, the get-started and the page, the client, the server, and the package that ships them.

